I've always found it odd that some people - often the minor or
mediocre - dare to lay claim to being successful writers. Everyone
knows (or should know) that like actors, the vast majority are out of
work for very long periods of time, and subsist on tiny incomes.
Orwell, Joyce, Kafka, Thomas - I very much doubt they could have
bought more than a plate of peas on the salaries they drew from
writing during their lifetimes. Yet this in no way reflects the
quality nor importance of their work. If you measure success in purely
fiscal terms, then almost by default you have to condemn those who
achieve success as poor writers, because the greater majority of top-
selling fiction is truly awful. The unintellectual city worker whose
greatest achievement is to have read 'Bridget Jones' Diary' without
needing to consult a dictionary demands light, pappy magazine prose
that can be guzzled down with a tuna wrap and diet coke.

Robert Aickman won one of his meagre two genre awards for a short
story that he was paid peanuts for. No doubt some (casts eyes towards
New Mexico) would thus accord him an unsuccessful writer.

I think you should ask everyone who joins alt.failed.writers to assume
a famous nom-de-plume, ideally those of talented writers who were
derided and scorned by the critics and publishers of the time.
