Very true: in  a nutshell, you *can*  make a  very good living from
writing, but almost never by writing really good  stuff that will still
be read  200 years from now.
Some first class writers have made it pay, - Graham greene ended his
days in the south of France; William Golding, well his first book made
it on to the big screen so presumably he did OK financially.
The top ten Best Sellers list is best regarded as a list of books it
would be a good idea to avoid - the average American's taste in reading,
if he/she reads more than the occasional magazine that is, is pretty
dire.  Childhood TV addiction and the education setup here are to blame
I suppose. (American readers of this group, of course, excepted!).

